article.headline: Arcain leads Comets to fourth straight win

images.name: Catchings Tamika 030708 vertical top
images.caption: Tiffani Johnson and the Comets were able to fend off the Fever.

article.linkText: Comets come back to knock off Fever
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Janeth Arcain scored 18 points, including the
last five of the game, leading the Houston Comets to a 60-56 win
over the Indiana Fever.

"I was just trying to play my game out there," Arcain said.
"I was not really trying to do anything different. I know I have
to play good defense out there and the shots will come. On that
last shot, the ball kind of slipped out of my hand and I heard
Ukari (Figgs) say 'Just shoot it.' I did and it went in."

Houston standout Sheryl Swoopes missed most of the first half
with a concussion. She returned for the second half and helped the
Comets win for the fifth time in the final game of a season-high
six-game homestand.

Swoopes scored all of her 15 points in the second half as the
Comets won their fourth consecutive game.

"I am just so proud of the way they held it together in the
first half," said Swoopes. She said she watched some of the game
while being evaluated in the locker room. "Overall, it is huge for
us to win four in a row right before the All-Star break. We kept
ourselves in position to win."

Leading 57-56, Arcain hit a 3-pointer as time expired on the
shot clock to give the Comets a four-point lead with just more than
10 seconds remaining.

Tamika Catchings scored a game-high 23 points for the Fever, 2-7
on the road and 9-7 overall.

"We really haven't figured out a way to win on the road this
year," said Catchings, whose team is a perfect 7-0 at home this
season. "We just seem to lose focus in the last seven to eight
minutes of every (road) game and we can't seem to get back in it."

Just 3:28 into the game, Swoopes collided with Nikki McCray in
front of the press table. The team issued a news release after the
game that said she suffered a concussion.

"I'm OK," Swoopes said. "I really don't know where (McCray)
came from. I just remember hitting her and then hitting the floor.
I have a headache now and my neck hurts a little bit, but I am just
glad that I am OK."

The Fever, who led 7-5 at that point, went on a 15-2 run to take
a 22-11 lead with 8:19 left in the half. But in the final 6:05, the
Comets outscored the Fever 12-5, highlighted by back-to-back
3-pointers from Ukari Figgs and Kelley Gibson.

Catchings led all scorers with 15 points at halftime.

Notes: Houston forward Tina Thompson (18.0 points per game)
missed Tuesday's game with a sprained left ankle suffered in the
closing minutes of Monday's team workout. She is listed as
day-to-day. ... Swoopes was voted the WNBA player of the week for
games played June 30-July 6. She averaged 21 points in the Comets'
two home wins over Minnesota and Washington. It was the fifth time
in her career she was player of the week.
